answer:
The first equation can be rewritten as $(x+3)^2 + (y-12)^2 = 121,$ so it represents a circle with center $(-3,12)$ and radius $11.$  The second equation can be rewritten as $(x+3)^2 - (y-8)^2 = -25,$ so it represents a hyperbola with center $(-3,8).$

We can then graph the two equations.

[asy]
unitsize(0.3 cm);

pair trans;

int i;

for (i = -10; i <= 10; ++i) {
  draw((i,-10)--(i,10),gray(0.7));
  draw((-10,i)--(10,i),gray(0.7));
}

draw(Circle((-3,12),11),red);
draw(((-3,8)--(-3,14)),blue);
draw((-3 + 5*dir(136.3),-3 + 5*dir(136.3 + 180))--(-3 + 5*dir(136.3 + 180)),blue);
draw((-3 + 5*dir(81.8),-3 + 5*dir(81.8 + 180))--(-3 + 5*dir(81.8 + 180)),blue);

label("$-10$", (-10,-10), S);
label("$-5$", (-5,-10), S);
label("$5$", (5,-10), S);
label("$10$", (10,-10), S);
label("$-10$", (-10,-10), W);
label("$-5$", (-10,-5), W);
label("$5$", (-10,5), W);
label("$10$", (-10,10), W);
label("$(-3,8)$", (-3,8), SW);
label("$(-3,12)$", (-3,12), SW);
label("$10$", (6,12), E);
label("$20$", (6,10), E);
label("$30$", (6,8), E);
[/asy]

We want to compute the sum of the distances from the four intersection points to $(-3,2).$  Note that $(-3,2)$ is the midpoint of $(-3,8)$ and $(-3,12),$ so the sum of the distances from the intersection points to $(-3,2)$ is equal to the sum of the distances from the intersection points to $(-3,8)$ and $(-3,12).$

We can use the property of hyperbolas that tells us that the difference of the distances from any point on the hyperbola to the foci is constant.  The sum of the distances from the intersection points to $(-3,8)$ and $(-3,12)$ is then equal to 2 times this constant.

Let $(-3, y)$ be a point on the hyperbola.  Then
$$\sqrt{(-3 + 3)^2 + (y - 8)^2} - \sqrt{(-3 + 3)^2 + (y - 12)^2} = 5.$$  (We use the fact that the distance between $(-3,8)$ and $(-3,12)$ is 4.)  Then $|y - 8| - |y - 12| = 5.$

If $y < 8,$ then $-(y - 8) - (-(y - 12)) = 5,$ which gives us $4 = 5.$  This is impossible.

If $8 \le y < 12,$ then $(y - 8) - (-(y - 12)) = 5,$ which gives us $y = 8.$  This is a solution.

If $y \ge 12,$ then $(y - 8) - (y - 12) = 5,$ which gives us $4 = 5.$  This is impossible.

Therefore, $y = 8,$ which means the sum of the distances from the intersection points to $(-3,8)$ and $(-3,12)$ is $2 \cdot 5 = 10.$

The answer is $\boxed{10}.$

