We can find the slopes of $\overline{PA}$ and $\overline{PB}$ as $\frac{0 - p}{vt - 0} = -\frac{p}{vt}$ and $\frac{0 - p}{3vt - 0} = -\frac{p}{3vt}$, respectively.  The tangent of $\angle APB$ is then given by the tangent subtraction formula:

\begin{align*}
\tan \angle APB &= \left| \frac{-\frac{p}{vt} - \left(-\frac{p}{3vt}\right)}{1 + \left(-\frac{p}{vt}\right)\left(-\frac{p}{3vt}\right)} \right| \\
&= \left| \frac{-\frac{2p}{3vt}}{1 + \frac{p^2}{3v^2 t^2}} \right| \\
&= \frac{\frac{2p}{3vt}}{1 + \frac{p^2}{3v^2 t^2}} \\
&= \frac{2p}{3vt + \frac{p^2}{vt}}.
\end{align*}By AM-GM, $3vt + \frac{p^2}{vt} \ge 2\sqrt{3vt \cdot \frac{p^2}{vt}} = 4p\sqrt{3}$, so $\frac{2p}{3vt + \frac{p^2}{vt}} \le \frac{2p}{4p\sqrt{3}} = \frac{1}{2\sqrt{3}}$.  Therefore, $\tan \angle APB \le \frac{1}{2\sqrt{3}}$, so $\angle APB \le \boxed{30^\circ}$.  This maximum is achieved when $3vt = \frac{p^2}{vt}$, or $vt = \frac{p}{\sqrt{3}}$.

