What is the degree measure of the smallest angle in triangle $PQS$?

answer:
Let $O$ be the center of the circle tangent to sides $\overline{AB}$ and $\overline{AC}$, and let $G$ be the intersection of angle bisectors $\overline{AP}$ and $\overline{AQ}$. Since $\triangle ABC$ is isosceles, $A$ lies on the angle bisector of $\angle POQ$, so $\angle POQ = 2\angle PAQ$. Since $\overline{AP}$ bisects $\angle OAQ$, $\angle OAQ = 2\angle PAQ = \angle POQ$, so $OQ = AQ = 1$. Then $\angle QOP = 60^\circ$, and similarly, $\angle QOS = 60^\circ$, so $\angle POS = 120^\circ$. Since $\overline{PS}$ is the angle bisector of $\angle POQ$, $\angle POQ = 60^\circ$, so $\angle PQS = \angle PSQ = 30^\circ$ and $\boxed{30^\circ}$ is the smallest angle of $\triangle PQS$. [asy]
size(200);
pair A, B, C, P, Q, R, S, O, G;
R=(0,0);
Q=(-2,0);
S=(2,0);
P=(1,1.732);
B=(-5.73,-1);
C=(3.732,-1);
A=(1.366,3.098);
O = (-1,0);
S = (1,0);
G = (-1.666,1.057);
draw(A--B--C--A);
draw(circle(P, 1));
draw(circle(Q, 1));
draw(circle(R, 1));
draw(circle(S, 1));
draw(A--P);
draw(A--Q);
draw(P--O--Q);
label("A", A, N);
label("B", B, SW);
label("C", C, SE);
dot(P);
dot(Q);
dot(R);
dot(S);
dot(O);
dot(G);
label("P", P, N);
label("Q", Q, SW);
label("R", R, SW);
label("S", S, SE);
