label("O", O, SE);
label("H", H, NW);
[/asy]

To reduce the total length of rope used, rope $HC$ and rope $HD$ are to be replaced by a single rope $HP$ where $P$ is a point on the straight line between $C$ and $D$. (The balloon remains at the same position $H$ above $O$ as described above.)  Determine the greatest length of rope that can be saved.

answer:
Let $CD$ be the diameter of the circle, with center $O$.  Then $CO = OD = 70$ m.  The balloon is at the center of the circle, so the shortest rope from $H$ to a point on $CD$ is the perpendicular from $H$ to $CD$.

[asy]
size(100);
defaultpen(linewidth(0.7));
pair A, B, C, D, O, H, W, X, Y, Z;
O=(0,0);
A=(1,1);
D=(1.5,-.3);
B=(-1.5,.3);
C=(-1,-1);
H=(0,2.5);
W=(5/3)*(A+D);
X=(5/3)*(A+B);
Y=(-1)*(W);
Z=(-1)*(X);
draw(W--X--Y--Z--W);
draw(A--C);
draw(B--D);
draw(O--H, linewidth(1));
draw(A--H, dashed);
draw(B--H, dashed);
draw(C--H, dashed);
draw(D--H, dashed);
dot(A);
dot(B);
dot(C);
dot(D);
dot(O);
dot(H);
label("A", A, NE);
label("B", B, SW);
label("C", C, SE);
label("D", D, NE);
label("O", O, SE);
label("H", H, NW);
pair P=extension(C, D, H, (0, -2.5));
draw(H--P, dashed);
label("P", P, S);
[/asy]

Let $HP$ be the perpendicular from $H$ to $CD$.  Then \begin{align*} HP^2 &= HC^2 - CO^2 \\ &= 150^2 - 70^2 \\ &= 16800, \end{align*}so $HP = 130$ m.  Similarly, the length of the perpendicular from $H$ to $AC$ is 120 m.

[asy]
size(100);
defaultpen(linewidth(0.7));
pair A, B, C, D, O, H, W, X, Y, Z;
O=(0,0);
A=(1,1);
D=(1.5,-.3);
B=(-1.5,.3);
C=(-1,-1);
H=(0,2.5);
W=(5/3)*(A+D);
X=(5/3)*(A+B);
Y=(-1)*(W);
Z=(-1)*(X);
draw(W--X--Y--Z--W);
draw(A--C);
draw(B--D);
draw(O--H, linewidth(1));
draw(A--H, dashed);
draw(B--H, dashed);
draw(C--H, dashed);
draw(D--H, dashed);
dot(A);
dot(B);
dot(C);
dot(D);
dot(O);
dot(H);
label("A", A, NE);
label("B", B, SW);
label("C", C, SE);
label("D", D, NE);
label("O", O, SE);
label("H", H, NW);
pair P=extension(C, D, H, (0, -2.5));
pair Q=extension(A, C, H, (0, -2.5));
draw(H--P, dashed);
draw(H--Q, dashed);
label("P", P, S);
label("Q", Q, NW);
[/asy]

Let $P$ be the point on $CD$ such that $HP$ is the perpendicular from $H$ to $CD$, and let $Q$ be the point on $AC$ such that $HQ$ is the perpendicular from $H$ to $AC$.  Then the total length of the four ropes is \begin{align*} HA + HB + HC + HD &= (HP + PA) + (HQ + QB) + HC + HD \\ &= (HP + HQ) + (PA + QB + HC + HD) \\ &\ge HP + HQ. \end{align*}The minimum of $HP + HQ$ occurs when $HPQ$ is collinear, in which case $HP + HQ = 130 + 120 = 250$ m.  The original total length of the four ropes is \begin{align*} HA + HB + HC + HD &= \sqrt{150^2 - 70^2} + \sqrt{130^2 - 70^2} + 150 + 130 \\ &= 130 + 120 + 150 + 130 \\ &= 530 \text{ m}. \end{align*}The greatest length of rope that can be saved is then $530 - 250 = \boxed{280}$ m.

