To reduce the total length of rope used, rope $HC$ and rope $HD$ are to be replaced by a single rope $HP$ where $P$ is a point on the straight line between $C$ and $D$. (The balloon remains at the same position $H$ above $O$ as described above.)  Determine the greatest length of rope that can be saved.

answer:
The total length of the four ropes is $ HA + HB + HC + HD $.  To minimize this total length, we will reflect the hot-air balloon $ H $ across the four cardinal directions to points $ H_A $, $ H_B $, $ H_C $, and $ H_D $, as shown.  The four ropes will then be straight lines from $ H $ to $ A $, $ B $, $ C $, and $ D $, which can be replaced by straight lines from $ H_A $ to $ A $, $ H_B $ to $ B $, $ H_C $ to $ C $, and $ H_D $ to $ D $.

[asy]
size(250);
pair A, B, C, D, O, H, HA, HB, HC, HD, W, X, Y, Z, P;
O=(0,0);
A=(1,1);
D=(1.5,-.3);
B=(-1.5,.3);
C=(-1,-1);
H=(0,2.5);
HA=(-H);
HB=(rotate(90)*(H));
HC=(rotate(-90)*(H));
HD=(rotate(180)*(H));
W=(5/3)*(A+D);
X=(5/3)*(A+B);
Y=(-1)*(W);
Z=(-1)*(X);
P=extension(C, D, HA, HD);
draw(W--X--Y--Z--W);
draw(A--C);
draw(B--D);
draw(O--H, linewidth(1));
draw(A--H, dashed);
draw(B--H, dashed);
draw(C--H, dashed);
draw(D--H, dashed);
draw(A--HA, dashed);
draw(B--HB, dashed);
draw(C--HC, dashed);
draw(D--HD, dashed);
draw(H--P, dashed);
dot(A);
dot(B);
dot(C);
dot(D);
dot(O);
dot(H);
dot(HA);
dot(HB);
dot(HC);
dot(HD);
label("A", A, NE);
label("B", B, SW);
label("C", C, SE);
label("D", D, NE);
label("O", O, SE);
label("H", H, NW);
label("H_A", HA, SW);
label("H_B", HB, N);
label("H_C", HC, dir(0));
label("H_D", HD, W);
label("P", P, SE);
[/asy]

We can then replace the four ropes with two ropes, one from $ H_A $ to $ H_C $ and the other from $ H_B $ to $ H_D $.  The intersection of these two ropes is point $ P $, which lies on $ CD $.  The length of rope $ HP $ is then equal to the length of segment $ H_PH $.

[asy]
size(250);
pair A, B, C, D, O, H, HA, HB, HC, HD, W, X, Y, Z, P;
O=(0,0);
A=(1,1);
D=(1.5,-.3);
B=(-1.5,.3);
C=(-1,-1);
H=(0,2.5);
HA=(-H);
HB=(rotate(90)*(H));
HC=(rotate(-90)*(H));
HD=(rotate(180)*(H));
W=(5/3)*(A+D);
X=(5/3)*(A+B);
Y=(-1)*(W);
Z=(-1)*(X);
P=extension(C, D, HA, HD);
draw(W--X--Y--Z--W);
draw(A--C);
draw(B--D);
draw(O--H, linewidth(1));
draw(A--H, dashed);
draw(B--H, dashed);
draw(C--H, dashed);
draw(D--H, dashed);
draw(A--HA, dashed);
draw(B--HB, dashed);
draw(C--HC, dashed);
draw(D--HD, dashed);
draw(H--P, dashed);
draw(HA--HC, dashed);
draw(HB--HD, dashed);
dot(A);
dot(B);
dot(C);
dot(D);
dot(O);
dot(H);
dot(HA);
dot(HB);
dot(HC);
dot(HD);
dot(P);
label("A", A, NE);
label("B", B, SW);
label("C", C, SE);
label("D", D, NE);
label("O", O, SE);
label("H", H, NW);
label("H_A", HA, SW);
label("H_B", HB, N);
label("H_C", HC, dir(0));
label("H_D", HD, W);
label("P", P, SE);
[/asy]

The greatest length of rope that can be saved is then equal to the difference between the total length of the four ropes and the total length of the two ropes, or
$$ HA + HB + HC + HD - H_PH. $$  Since $ HA = H_PH $, $ HB = H_PH $, $ HC = H_PH $, and $ HD = H_PH $, this is equal to
$$ 2(HA + HB + HC + HD) - 4H_PH. $$  To minimize this expression, we must minimize $ H_PH $, which occurs when $ P $ is the midpoint of $ CD $.  In this case, $ H_PH = \sqrt{H_PO^2 + OP^2} = \sqrt{15^2 + 70^2} = 75 $, so the greatest length of rope that can be saved is
$$ 2(150 + 130) - 4(75) = \boxed{140}. $$

