label("$A$", A, N);
label("$B$", B, SW);
label("$C$", C, SE);
label("$D$", D, NW);
label("$M$", M, S);
[/asy]

answer:
Let $x = \angle BAC.$  Then $\angle BDC = 3x,$ and $\angle BDM = 2x.$  Also, $\angle BMD = 90^\circ,$ so $\angle CBM = 90^\circ - x.$  Since $\angle BAC$ and $\angle ABC$ are complementary, $\angle ABC = 90^\circ - x.$

Since $AB = AC,$ $\angle ABC = \angle ACB = 90^\circ - x.$  Hence, $\angle BMC = 2x.$  Since $\angle BMD = 90^\circ,$ $\angle CMD = 90^\circ - 2x.$

We can now use right triangle $BMD$ to find $\sin x$ and $\cos x$ in terms of the sides of the triangle.
[asy]
unitsize(0.4 cm);

pair A, B, C, D, M;

A = (0,11);
D = (0,1);
B = (-11/2,0);
C = (11/2,0);
M = (B + C)/2;

draw(A--B--C--cycle);
draw(A--M);
draw(B--D--C);

label("$A$", A, N);
label("$B$", B, SW);
label("$C$", C, SE);
label("$D$", D, NW);
label("$M$", M, S);
[/asy]

From right triangle $BMD,$ we see that
$$\sin x = \frac{10}{BM} \quad \text{and} \quad \cos x = \frac{1}{BM}.$$Note that $BM^2 = BC^2/4 = AB^2 - AM^2 = AB^2 - 121,$ so
$$\sin x = \frac{10}{\sqrt{AB^2 - 121}} \quad \text{and} \quad \cos x = \frac{1}{\sqrt{AB^2 - 121}}.$$By the Double Angle Formula,
$$\sin 2x = 2 \sin x \cos x = \frac{20}{AB^2 - 121}.$$By the Law of Sines, $\frac{AB}{\sin 2x} = \frac{BM}{\sin 3x}.$  Hence,
$$\frac{AB}{20/(AB^2 - 121)} = \frac{11/2}{\sin 3x}.$$We can use the angle triple formula to evaluate $\sin 3x$:  $\sin 3x = 3 \sin x - 4 \sin^3 x.$  Then
$$\sin 3x = \frac{30}{AB^2 - 121} - \frac{1200}{(AB^2 - 121)^3} = \frac{30(AB^2 + 39)}{(AB^2 - 121)^3}.$$Then
$$\frac{AB}{20/(AB^2 - 121)} = \frac{11/2}{30(AB^2 + 39)/(AB^2 - 121)^3}.$$Cross-multiplying (and simplifying) gives $AB^4 - 242 AB^2 = 0,$ so $AB^2 = 242.$  Thus, the perimeter of $\triangle ABC$ is $3(AB) = \boxed{33 \sqrt{2}}.$

question:
Triangle $ABC$ is isosceles, with $AB=AC$ and altitude $AM=11.$ Suppose that there is a point $D$ on $\overline{AM}$ with $AD=10$ and $\angle BDC=3\angle BAC.$  Find the perimeter of triangle $ABC.$

[asy]
unitsize(0.4 cm);

pair A, B, C, D, M;

A = (0,11);
D = (0,1);
B = (-11/2,0);
C = (11/2,0);
M = (B + C)/2;

draw(A--B--C--cycle);
draw(A--M);
draw(B--D--C);

label("$A$", A, N);
label("$B$", B, SW);
label("$C$", C, SE);
label("$D$", D, NW);
label("$M$", M, S);
[/asy]

answer:
Let $x = \angle BAC.$  Then $\angle BDC = 3x,$ and
$$\angle BDM = \angle BDC - \angle DMC = 3x - (90^\circ - x) = 4x - 90^\circ.$$Furthermore, $\angle DBM = \angle ABM - \angle ABM = 45^\circ - x.$  Hence, in triangle $BDM,$
$$\frac{BD}{\sin (45^\circ - x)} = \frac{10}{\sin (4x - 90^\circ)} = \frac{DM}{\sin (45^\circ + x)}.$$Since $\sin (4x - 90^\circ) = -\cos 4x,$ this becomes
$$\frac{BD}{\sin (45^\circ - x)} = \frac{DM}{\sin (45^\circ + x)} = \frac{10}{\cos 4x}.$$By the Law of Sines in triangle $BDC,$
$$\frac{BD}{\sin 3x} = \frac{10}{\sin 120^\circ} = \frac{20}{\sqrt{3}}.$$Hence,
$$BD = \frac{20}{\sqrt{3}} \sin 3x = \frac{20}{\sqrt{3}} (3 \sin x - 4 \sin^3 x).$$Also,
$$\cos 4x = 1 - 8 \sin^2 x + 8 \sin^4 x = 8 \sin^4 x - 8 \sin^2 x + 1.$$Thus,
$$\frac{BD}{\sin (45^\circ - x)} = \frac{\frac{20}{\sqrt{3}} (3 \sin x - 4 \sin^3 x)}{\frac{\sqrt{2}}{2} (\cos x - \sin x)} = \frac{40}{\sqrt{6}} (3 \sin x - 4 \sin^3 x) = \frac{20}{\sqrt{3}} \cdot \frac{2}{\sqrt{2}} (3 \sin x - 4 \sin^3 x) = \frac{20}{\sqrt{3}} \cdot \frac{2}{\sqrt{2}} \sin x (3 - 4 \sin^2 x).$$Setting this equal to $\frac{10}{\cos 4x},$ we get
$$\frac{20}{\sqrt{3}} \cdot \frac{2}{\sqrt{2}} \sin x (3 - 4 \sin^2 x) = \frac{10}{8 \sin^4 x - 8 \sin^2 x + 1}.$$Let $y = \sin^2 x.$  Then
$$\frac{20}{\sqrt{3}} \cdot \frac{2}{\sqrt{2}} \sin x (3 - 4 \sin^2 x) = \frac{10}{8 \sin^4 x - 8 \sin^2 x + 1}.$$Hence,
$$\frac{40}{\sqrt{6}} \sqrt{y} (3 - 4y) = \frac{10}{8y^2 - 8y + 1}.$$Let $z = \sqrt{y}.$  Then
$$\frac{40}{\sqrt{6}} z (3 - 4z^2) = \frac{10}{8z^4 - 8z^2 + 1}.$$Cross-multiplying, we get
$$4z (3 - 4z^2) (8z^4 - 8z^2 + 1) = \frac{\sqrt{6}}{4}.$$Expanding, we get
$$-32z^7 + 48z^5 - 8z^3 + 3z = \frac{\sqrt{6}}{4}.$$The only solution is $z = \frac{1}{2},$ which gives $y = \frac{1}{4}$ and $x = \arcsin \frac{1}{2} = 30^\circ.$  (Note that $x = 150^\circ$ does not work, as it makes $D$ lie outside of segment $AM.$)

[asy]
unitsize(1 cm);

pair A, B, C, D, M;

A = (0,11);
D = (0,1);
B = (-11/2,0);
C = (11/2,0);
M = (B + C)/2;

draw(A--B--C--cycle);
draw(A--M);
draw(B--D--C);

label("$A$", A, N);
label("$B$", B, SW);
label("$C$", C, SE);
label("$D$", D, NW);
label("$M$", M, S);
[/asy]

Thus, $\angle BAC = 30^\circ,$ $\angle ABC = 75^\circ,$ and $\angle ACB = 75^\circ.$  The perimeter of triangle $ABC$ is
$$AB + BC + CA = AB + 2 \cdot BC.$$Since $\angle ABC = 75^\circ,$ $AM = 11,$ and $\angle ABM = 45^\circ,$ we find that
$$AB = \frac{11}{\sin 75^\circ} = \frac{11}{\frac{\sqrt{6} + \sqrt{2}}{4}} = 22 (\sqrt{6} - \sqrt{2}).$$Also,
$$\frac{BM}{\sin 30^\circ} = \frac{11}{\sin 75^\circ} = \frac{22}{\sqrt{6} + \sqrt{2}},$$so $BM = \frac{11}{\sqrt{6} + \sqrt{2}} = \frac{11 (\sqrt{6} - \sqrt{2})}{4}.$  Then
$$BC = 2 \cdot BM = \frac{11 (\sqrt{6} - \sqrt{2})}{2}.$$Hence, the perimeter of triangle $ABC$ is
$$22 (\sqrt{6} - \sqrt{2}) + 2 \cdot \frac{11 (\sqrt{6} - \sqrt{2})}{2} = \boxed{33 (\sqrt{6} - \sqrt{2})}.$$

