Next, we use the Law of Cosines on triangle $BDC$ to get
$$BC^2 = BD^2 + CD^2 - 2 \cdot BD \cdot CD \cos 120^\circ = BD^2 + CD^2 + BD \cdot CD.$$Since $BD = AM - AD = 11 - 10 = 1,$ and $BD = CD$ because $\triangle ABC$ is isosceles, we have
$$BC^2 = 3BD^2 = 3,$$so $BC = \sqrt{3}.$

Finally, we use the Pythagorean Theorem on triangle $ABM$ to get $AB = \sqrt{11^2 + 1^2} = \sqrt{122}.$  The perimeter of $\triangle ABC$ is then $2AB + BC = 2 \sqrt{122} + \sqrt{3}.$

