answer:
Let $x = \angle BAC.$  Since $\triangle ABC$ is isosceles, the base angles are both $180^\circ - 2x,$ so
$$\angle BDC = 3x = 180^\circ - 2(180^\circ - 2x) = 4x - 180^\circ.$$Then $x = 60^\circ.$

[asy]
unitsize(0.75 cm);

pair A, B, C, D, M;

A = (0,11);
D = (0,1);
B = (-11/2,0);
C = (11/2,0);
M = (B + C)/2;

draw(A--B--C--cycle);
draw(A--M);
draw(B--D--C);

label("$A$", A, N);
label("$B$", B, SW);
label("$C$", C, SE);
label("$D$", D, NW);
label("$M$", M, S);
[/asy]

Let $y = BM = MC.$  By the Law of Cosines on triangle $ABM,$
$$AB^2 = y^2 + 11^2 - 2y \cdot 11 \cdot \cos 60^\circ = y^2 - 11y + 121 = (y - 11)^2.$$Thus, $AB = y - 11.$

By the Law of Cosines on triangle $BDC,$
$$BC^2 = y^2 + 1^2 - 2y \cdot 1 \cdot \cos 120^\circ = y^2 + y + 1.$$Since $BC = 2y,$ $4y^2 = y^2 + y + 1,$ which simplifies to $y^2 - y - 1 = 0.$  By the Law of Cosines on triangle $ABD,$
$$BD^2 = y^2 + 10^2 - 2y \cdot 10 \cdot \cos 60^\circ = y^2 - 10y + 100 = (y - 5)^2.$$Thus, $BD = y - 5.$

By the Law of Cosines on triangle $BDC,$
$$BC^2 = BD^2 + DC^2 - 2 \cdot BD \cdot DC \cos 3x.$$Then
\begin{align*}
y^2 + y + 1 &= (y - 5)^2 + (2y - 1)^2 - 2 \cdot (y - 5) \cdot (2y - 1) \cos 180^\circ \\
&= y^2 - 10y + 25 + 4y^2 - 4y + 1 + (y - 5)(2y - 1) \\
&= 6y^2 - 14y + 26 + 2y^2 - 11y + 5 \\
&= 8y^2 - 25y + 31.
\end{align*}Then $7y^2 - 24y + 30 = 0,$ which factors as $(7y - 10)(y - 3) = 0.$  Since $y \neq \frac{10}{7},$ we have $y = 3.$

The perimeter of triangle $ABC$ is $2y + (y - 11) = 3y - 11 = 3(3) - 11 = \boxed{-2}.$

