The vector $\begin{pmatrix} 4 \\ 3 \end{pmatrix} - \begin{pmatrix} 5 \\ 0 \end{pmatrix} = \begin{pmatrix} -1 \\ 3 \end{pmatrix}$ is the image of the vector $\begin{pmatrix} 5 \\ 0 \end{pmatrix}.$  Let $\begin{pmatrix} a \\ b \end{pmatrix}$ be the line of reflection.  Then the line perpendicular to $\begin{pmatrix} a \\ b \end{pmatrix}$ passing through $\begin{pmatrix} 5 \\ 0 \end{pmatrix}$ is the perpendicular bisector of the segment from $\begin{pmatrix} 5 \\ 0 \end{pmatrix}$ to $\begin{pmatrix} 4 \\ 3 \end{pmatrix}.$  This perpendicular bisector is given by
$$y - 0 = -\frac{a}{b} \left( x - 5 \right).$$The vector $\begin{pmatrix} a \\ b \end{pmatrix}$ is a unit vector, so $a^2 + b^2 = 1.$  Also, since $\begin{pmatrix} a \\ b \end{pmatrix}$ lies on the perpendicular bisector, we have
$$\frac{3}{4} = -\frac{a}{b} \left( \frac{9}{4} \right)$$and
$$\frac{4}{3} = -\frac{a}{b} \left( \frac{16}{3} \right).$$Solving, we find $a = -\frac{1}{\sqrt{10}}$ and $b = \frac{3}{\sqrt{10}}.$

