answer:
The locus of points equidistant from two points is the perpendicular bisector of the segment joining the two points. Thus, the set of points equidistant from $O$ and $A$ lies on the perpendicular bisector of segment $\overline{OA}$, as shown in the following diagram: [asy]
size(200);
draw((-250,100)--(250,100)--(250,-100)--(-250,-100)--cycle);
dot((0,0));
label("$O$",(0,0),N);
label("$A$",(-250,100),NW); label("$B$",(250,100),NE); label("$C$",(250,-100),SE); label("$D$",(-250,-100),SW);
draw((250,100)--(-250,-100));
draw((250,-100)--(-250,100));
draw((0,100)--(0,-100));
[/asy] Thus, the set of points equidistant from $O$ and $B$ lies on the perpendicular bisector of segment $\overline{OB}$, the set of points equidistant from $O$ and $C$ lies on the perpendicular bisector of segment $\overline{OC}$, and the set of points equidistant from $O$ and $D$ lies on the perpendicular bisector of segment $\overline{OD}$. The locus of points closer to $O$ than to any of the four vertices is the region bounded by these four lines, as shown: [asy]
size(200);
draw((-250,100)--(250,100)--(250,-100)--(-250,-100)--cycle);
dot((0,0));
label("$O$",(0,0),N);
label("$A$",(-250,100),NW); label("$B$",(250,100),NE); label("$C$",(250,-100),SE); label("$D$",(-250,-100),SW);
draw((0,100)--(0,-100));
draw((250,100)--(-250,-100));
draw((250,-100)--(-250,100));
fill((0,0)--(250,250*k)--(250,-250*k)--cycle, black);
[/asy] To compute the probability that a randomly chosen point from the interior of rectangle $ABCD$ is in this region, we compute the ratio of the area of the triangle to the area of the rectangle. The area of the triangle is $$\frac{1}{2}(AB)(AD)k = \frac{1}{2}(2r)(2rk)k = 2rk^2.$$The area of the rectangle is $(AB)(AD) = (2r)(2rk) = 4rk.$ Hence, the probability is $$\frac{2rk^2}{4rk} = \boxed{\frac{k}{2}}.$$

