Let $r$ be a real root of the equation, so
$$r^4 + ar^3 - br^2 + ar + 1 = 0.$$If $r = 0,$ then $1 = 0,$ which is impossible.  Hence, $r \neq 0,$ and we can divide by $r^2,$ to get
$$r^2 + ar - b + \frac ar + \frac 1{r^2} = 0.$$Then
$$\left(r + \frac 1{r}\right)^2 + a\left(r + \frac 1r\right) - b = 0.$$If $r > 0,$ then by AM-GM, $r + \frac 1r \ge 2.$  Hence, we can write $r + \frac 1r = 2 \cos \theta,$ where $\theta \in [0, \pi).$  (Note that for $r < 0,$ $r + \frac 1r$ can also take on all values in $(-\infty, -2].$)

