label("$2$", (0,2.5), E);

label("$y=x+1$", (2.5,2.5), N);
label("$y=x-1$", (2.5,2.5), N);
[/asy]

Then $(r + \frac 1r)^2 = 4 \cos^2 \theta,$ so $4 \cos^2 \theta + 2a \cos \theta - b = 0.$  This equation has a solution $|\theta| \le 1$ if and only if the graph of $y = 4 \cos^2 \theta + 2a \cos \theta$ and the line $y = b$ intersect.

The graph of $y = 4 \cos^2 \theta + 2a \cos \theta$ is a parabola opening upward with vertex at $(-a, -a^2).$  Thus, the graph of $y = 4 \cos^2 \theta + 2a \cos \theta$ intersects the line $y = b$ if and only if $b \ge -a^2.$  Hence, the set of points $(a, b)$ is the region bounded by the parabola $y = -x^2.$

